article.headline: Portland extends Phoenix road woes
article.linkText: Mercury ties mark with 16th straight road loss
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. -- The Portland Fire took full advantage of a
timely visit from the struggling Phoenix Mercury.

DeMya Walker scored 17 points and Alisa Burras added 10 as
Portland beat Phoenix 73-61 on Wednesday, the Mercury's WNBA-record
tying 16th consecutive road loss.

Phoenix has not won a road game since last July 27 at Seattle,
and has lost eight of nine overall. Portland was coming off a loss
to Los Angeles on Friday night that snapped a seven-game winning
streak.

"I don't think we wanted to focus too much on the fact that we
lost to L.A.,'' Walker said. "We knew that we were going to play
well because yesterday in practice everybody was focused, everybody
was playing hard, playing aggressive.

"When we're on the court, we believe. From top to bottom, we
have faith in everybody. That's just the attitude everybody has.''

Walker has been Portland's leading scorer in each of the last
five games

"DeMya has made such tremendous strides over the last two-plus
years,'' Portland coach Linda Hargrove said. "She is coming into
her own right now and she is so confident. She's the go-to player
for us right now. We like seeing the ball in her hands when we have
to score.''

Gordana Grubin led the Mercury with 21 points, six rebounds and
five assists. Jennifer Gillom had 15 points and five rebounds, and
Lisa Harrison added 13 points.

"I thought we started the game strong, but we just can't finish
games,'' Phoenix coach Linda Sharp said. "It goes right back to
decision-making and protection of the ball and executing our plays.
In the second half we had too many turnovers and we misread on
switches and didn't see open players. We didn't read what the
defense was doing.''

The Fire took a 10-point lead seven minutes into the second
half, but an 11-1 Phoenix run got the Mercury back in the game and
they eventually took a one-point lead.

Portland finished strong, and sent the Mercury to their 10th
straight road loss this season. Phoenix tied the road futility
record set by Washington in the 1998 and 1999 seasons.

Portland used a 17-4 run midway through the first half to
overcome some poor shooting early and take a 32-36 halftime lead.
After starting the game 3-of-13 from the field, the Fire rebounded
to shoot 43 percent for the half.

"This was a game we knew we needed to have,'' Hargrove said.
"We knew this was a team we'd have to beat out to be in the top
four. I thought Phoenix played a great ballgame and I felt like we
had to do a lot of good things, especially late, in order to win.''

Jackie Stiles made her return to the Portland lineup after
spending the previous seven games on the injured list with bursitis
in her right heel. Stiles had three points on 1-of-2 shooting in 11
minutes.

"I felt very good, the best I've felt all year as far as my
foot, the rest has helped it a lot,'' Stiles said. "I've never
missed a game in college, so I've never dealt with anything like
this. It's been very tough.''

Stiles said she's also seen some improvement in her right wrist,
which was operated on in the offseason.

"What I'm most happy with is my wrist,'' she said. "I was
really thinking I was going to have to retire there if it didn't
get any better, because it was just so tough to shoot with a wrist
you can't bend.''
